==English==
===Etymology 1===
[[you]] + [[-s]] ''plural suffix''
====Alternative spellings====
*[[yous]]
====Pronoun====
'''youse'''

#(''regional'') You (plural). Sometimes as '''youse guys'''
#(''New York'') You (singular).
====Usage note====
''Youse'' as a plural is found in [[Australia]], [[Glasgow]] in [[Scotland]], parts of the northern [[United States]]. ''Youse'' as a singular is found in [[New York]].
====Synonyms====
*[[you]]
*[[you guys]]
*[[y'all]] (''US'')
*[[you-uns]] (''US'')
*[[you fella]] (''Australian Aboriginal'')
===Etymology 2===
Contraction of ''[[you]] [[is]]''.
====Alternative spellings====
*[[you's]]
====Contraction====
'''youse'''

#(''[[AAVE]]'') [[you]] [[are]], [[you're]]
====Usage notes====
The standard contraction for ''you is'' is ''you's'' (e.g., ''Talking to you's always fun.'').  In transcribing the AAVE usage of ''you is'' where standard English has ''you are'', either ''you's'' or ''youse'' is used.  E.g, either ''You's a damn fool'' or ''Youse a damn fool'' but never ''Talking to youse always fun''.
